abstract: How Ocean City cleared the gulls from its boardwalk — with falcons and hawks.
snippet: How Ocean City cleared the gulls from its boardwalk — with falcons and hawks.
lead_paragraph: The war between humans and gulls in Ocean City, N.J., reached a turning point in 2019. In the years leading up to then, the town’s populations of great black-backed, ring-billed, laughing and herring gulls had become increasingly comfortable snatching beachgoers’ French fries, potato chips and other finger foods. One day that spring, Ocean City’s mayor, Jay Gillian, watched as a gull swooped into a stroller on the boardwalk and stole a slice of pizza from a toddler’s hands. The mayor swears he saw blood on the little girl’s face, though he admits it may have been sauce. The town’s brand — its slogan is “America’s Greatest Family Resort” — was being sullied.

main: The Ancient Art of Falconry at the Jersey Shore

abstract: They are voting at higher rates than younger adults once did, helping the Democratic Party.
snippet: They are voting at higher rates than younger adults once did, helping the Democratic Party.
lead_paragraph: In the 2018 elections — the midterms of Donald Trump’s presidency — turnout among younger voters surged. Almost twice as many people in their late 20s and early 30s voted that year as had done so in the midterms four years earlier. And they strongly backed Democratic candidates, helping the party retake control of Congress.

abstract: The Broadway musical and its Tony-winning star, Alice Ripley, return to the stage in this condensed and deconstructed production.
snippet: The Broadway musical and its Tony-winning star, Alice Ripley, return to the stage in this condensed and deconstructed production.
lead_paragraph: BARCELONA, Spain — When Tom Kitt and Brian Yorkey began writing their 2008 rock musical, “Next to Normal,” they wanted to create a piece in which, according to Yorkey, they could “bring the audience into the mind of the main character.” That character, Diana Goodman, is a suburban wife and mother with bipolar disorder who grapples with the harrowing symptoms of her mental illness while trying to maintain a functional life.

main: An Immersive ‘Next to Normal’ Debuts in Barcelona
print_headline: Deconstructed and Yet Still ‘Next to Normal’

abstract: Patriarchy and pantheism in the American West.
snippet: Patriarchy and pantheism in the American West.
lead_paragraph: I wrote a little bit about “Yellowstone” after my family’s cross-country road trip last summer, linking the hit soap opera to ongoing debates about land use and development and conservation in the American West. My column described the series as very “red state” and cited a very blue-state essay in which the author, Vulture’s Kathryn VanArendonk, described being drawn into the show almost in spite of herself. With its portrait of an embattled but sympathetic white male patriarch defending a cowboy way of life against coastal money and Californian transplants, it didn’t seem controversial to present the show as leaning rightward.

main: Right Wing or Woke? The Complicated Politics of ‘Yellowstone.’
